htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: When an herbivore eats a plant , the energy in the plant tissues is used by the herbivore .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: But how much of that energy is transferred to the herbivore ?

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Remember that plants are producers , bringing the energy into the ecosystem by converting sunlight into glucose .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Does the plant use some of the energy for its own needs ?

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Recall the energy is the ability to do work , and the plant has plenty or `` work '' to do .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: So of course it needs and uses energy .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: After the plant uses the energy from glucose for its own needs , the excess energy is available to the organism that eats the plant .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: The herbivore uses the energy from the plant to power its own life processes and to build more body tissues .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: However , only about 10 % of the total energy from the plant gets stored in the herbivoreâs body as extra body tissue .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: The rest of the energy is used by the herbivore and released as heat .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: The next consumer on the food chain that eats the herbivore will only store about 10 % of the total energy from the herbivore in its own body .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: This means the carnivore will store only about 1 % of the total energy that was originally in the plant .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: In other words , only about 10 % of energy of one step in a food chain is stored in the next step in the food chain .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: The majority of the energy is used by the organism or released to the environment .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Every time energy is transferred from one organism to another , there is a loss of energy .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: This loss of energy can be shown in an energy pyramid .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Since there is energy loss at each step in a food chain , it takes many producers to support just a few carnivores in a community .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Each step of the food chain in the energy pyramid is called a trophic level .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Plants or other photosynthetic organisms ( autotrophs ) are found on the first trophic level , at the bottom of the pyramid .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: The next level will be the herbivores , and then the carnivores that eat the herbivores .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: The energy pyramid ( Figure below ) shows four levels of a food chain , from producers to carnivores .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Because of the high rate of energy loss in food chains , there are usually only 4 or 5 trophic levels in the food chain or energy pyramid .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: There just is not enough energy to support any additional trophic levels .

htext: energy pyramid model is used to show the pattern of traits that are passed from one generation to the next in a family ?
mtext: Heterotrophs are found in all levels of an energy pyramid other than the first level .

mtext: One possible answer is that helping others often means helping close relatives .

mtext: Although the concept of biodiversity did not become a vital component of biology and political science until nearly 40 years after Aldo Leopoldâs death in 1948 , Leopold â often considered the father of modern ecology - would have likely found the term an appropriate description of his âcogs and wheels.â Literally , biodiversity is the many different kinds ( diversity ) of life ( bio- ) .

mtext: Species diversity best fits the literal translation : the number of different species in a particular ecosystem or on Earth .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between measurement , form , and function
mtext: A second measure recognizes variation within a species : differences among individuals or populations make up genetic diversity .

mtext: Finally , as Leopold clearly understood , the âcogs and wheelsâ include not only life but also the land , sea , and air that support life .

mtext: Recall that the molecular formula shows the number of each atom that occurs in a molecule of that compound .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: Hydrogen ( H 2 ) is an example of an element that exists naturally as a diatomic molecule .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: A diatomic molecule is a molecule containing two atoms .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: Most atoms attain a lower potential energy when they are bonded to other atoms than when they are separated .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: Consider two isolated hydrogen atoms that are separated by a distance large enough to prevent any interaction between them .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: Figure 62.1 The graph shows how the potential energy of two hydrogen atoms changes as a function of their separation distance .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: Now there are several interactions which begin to occur .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: Eventually , a position is reached where the potential energy is at its lowest possible point .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: If the hydrogen atoms move any closer together , a third interaction begins to dominate and that is the repulsive force between the two positively-charged nuclei .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: The point at which the potential energy reached its minimum represents the ideal distance between hydrogen atoms for a stable chemical bond to occur .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: This type of chemical bond is called a covalent bond .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: A covalent bond is a bond in which two atoms share one or more pairs of electrons .

htext: A scientific explanation should include a demonstration of the relationships between changes , interactions , and formulas
mtext: The single electrons from each of the two hydrogen atoms are shared when the atoms come together to form a hydrogen molecule ( H 2 ) .

mtext: A chemical compound is a new substance that forms when atoms of two or more elements react with one another .

mtext: A chemical reaction is a process that changes some chemical substances into other chemical substances .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: Like a chemical compound , a mixture consists of more than one chemical substance .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: Unlike a compound , a mixture does not have a fixed chemical composition .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: The substances in a mixture can be combined in any proportions .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: A mixture also does not involve a chemical reaction .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: Therefore , the substances in a mixture are not changed into unique new substances , and they can be separated from each other without a chemical reaction .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: The following examples illustrate these differences between mixtures and compounds .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: When iron filings and sulfur powder are mixed together in any ratio , they form a mixture .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: A magnet can be used to mechanically separate the two elements by attracting the iron filings out of the mixture and leaving the sulfur behind .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: A magnet can not be used to mechanically separate the iron from the iron sulfide because metallic iron does not exist in the compound .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: It would have remained that way except for the development of technology .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: Using technology , scientists would find more evidence that continents had drifted .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a magnet
mtext: They would also be able to find the mechanism .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a glass cup
mtext: Glass is a very important amorphous solid that is made by cooling a mixture of materials in such a way that it does not crystallize .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a glass cup
mtext: Glass is sometimes referred to as a supercooled liquid rather than a solid .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a glass cup
mtext: Instead , as glass is heated , it slowly softens and can be shaped into all sorts of interesting forms .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a glass cup
mtext: When a glass object shatters , it does so in a very irregular way , unlike crystalline solids , which always break into fragments that have the same shape as dictated by its crystal system .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a glass cup
mtext: Unlike crystalline solids that have regular planes of cleavage , the physical properties of amorphous solids are the same in all directions .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT a glass cup
mtext: Plastics are used for many purposes because they are inexpensive to produce and do not shatters like glass or ceramic materials .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: A homogeneous mixture is a mixture in which the composition is uniform throughout the mixture .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: The salt water described above is homogeneous because the dissolved salt is evenly distributed throughout the entire salt water sample .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: Often it is easy to confuse a homogeneous mixture with a pure substance because they are both uniform .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: The amount of salt in the salt water can vary from one sample to another .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: All solutions would be considered homogeneous because the dissolved material is present in the same amount throughout the solution .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: Since each part of the mixture has not reacted with another part of the mixture , the identities of the different materials is unchanged .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: The components of a mixture keep their own identity when they combine , so they retain their physical properties .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: Water has a lower boiling point than salt , and it evaporates in the heat of the sun .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water

mtext: Figure 28.14 Q : Suppose you have a mixture of salt and pepper .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: If you mix salt and pepper with water , only the salt will dissolve , leaving the pepper floating in the water .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: You can separate the pepper from the water by pouring the mixture through a filter , such as a coffee filter .

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: Q : After you separate the pepper from the salt water , how could you separate the salt from the water ?

htext: All of the following would be helpful in separating a mixture of sand and salt EXCEPT water
mtext: A : You could heat the water until it boils and evaporates .

mtext: The salt would be left behind .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: The process in which organ systems work to maintain a stable internal environment is called homeostasis .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Here are just three of the many ways that human organ systems help the body maintain homeostasis : Respiratory system : A high concentration of carbon dioxide in the blood triggers faster breathing .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: The lungs exhale more frequently , which removes carbon dioxide from the body more quickly .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Excretory system : A low level of water in the blood triggers retention of water by the kidneys .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: The kidneys produce more concentrated urine , so less water is lost from the body .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Endocrine system : A high concentration of sugar in the blood triggers secretion of insulin by an endocrine gland called the pancreas .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Insulin is a hormone that helps cells absorb sugar from the blood .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: The regulation of your internal environment is done primarily through negative feedback .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Essentially , it `` shuts off '' or `` turns on '' a system when it varies from a set value .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: During a winter day , in your house a thermostat senses the temperature in a room and responds by turning on or off the heater .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Your body acts in much the same way .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: When body temperature rises , receptors in the skin and the brain sense the temperature change .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: The temperature change triggers a command from the brain .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: If you are too hot , the skin makes sweat and blood vessels near the skin surface dilate .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Another example of negative feedback has to do with blood glucose levels .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: When glucose ( sugar ) levels in the blood are too high , the pancreas secretes insulin to stimulate the absorption of glucose and the conversion of glucose into glycogen , which is stored in the liver .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: As blood glucose levels decrease , less insulin is produced .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: When glucose levels are too low , another hormone called glucagon is produced , which causes the liver to convert glycogen back to glucose .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: If a raise in body temperature ( stimulus ) is detected ( receptor ) , a signal will cause the brain to maintain homeostasis ( response ) .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Once the body temperature returns to normal , negative feedback will cause the response to end .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: This sequence of stimulus-receptor-signal-response is used throughout the body to maintain homeostasis .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: This is the job of the excretory system .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: You remove waste as a gas ( carbon dioxide ) , as a liquid ( urine and sweat ) , and as a solid .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Excretion is the process of removing wastes and excess water from the body .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Recall that carbon dioxide travels through the blood and is transferred to the lungs where it is exhaled .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: In the large intestine , the remains of food are turned into solid waste for excretion .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: How is waste other than carbon dioxide removed from the blood ?

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: That is the role of the kidneys .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Urine is a liquid waste formed by the kidneys as they filter the blood .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Sometimes your body is low on water and trying to reduce the amount of water lost in urine .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Your body is striving to maintain homeostasis through the process of excretion .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Your body also needs to remove the wastes that build up from cell activity and from digestion .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: The organs of your excretory system help to release wastes from the body .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: The organs of the excretory system are also parts of other organ systems .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: For example , your lungs are part of the respiratory system .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: Your lungs remove carbon dioxide from your body , so they are also part of the excretory system .

htext: The human respiratory system is responsible for removing carbon dioxide from blood
mtext: More organs of the excretory system are listed below ( Table below ) .

mtext: Organ ( s ) Function Component of Other Organ System Lungs Remove carbon dioxide .
